title: Nielsens: 'Walking Dead,' 'Leno's Garage'
text:
Who doesn't love a walker parade, especially with 'The Walking Dead's' Daryl Dixon (Norman Reedus) as the motorcyle-riding grand marshal? (Photo: Gene Page, AMC)
CONNECT 4 TWEET LINKEDIN COMMENT EMAIL MORE Watching Dead . The Walking Dead roared back with its Season 6 premiere, averaging 14.6 million viewers Sunday to finish No. 1 for the week in cable and trailing only CBS’ NCIS (16.9 million) and The Big Bang Theory (15.4 million) among non-sports programs. It was down 16% from 2014’s record fall premiere (17.3 million viewers). Dead topped all cable and broadcast programs in advertiser-prized young adults.
Gaga power. American Horror Story ’s Hotel edition, which features music superstar Lady Gaga, premiered Wednesday with 5.8 million viewers, down just 5% from last fall’s best-ever opener for the anthology series. It finished far ahead of Fox’s Scream Queens (3 million on Tuesday), a new series from the creative braintrust behind Horror Story .
Angela Bassett plays Ramona Royale in FX's 'American Horror Story: Hotel.' (Photo: Suzanne Tenner, FX)
October openers. CW, launching its fall lineup a couple of weeks after other broadcast networks, offered a heaping helping of season premieres: The Flash (3.6 million viewers) and iZombie (1.5 million) on Tuesday; Arrow (2.7 million) and Supernatural (1.9 million) on Wednesday; The Nina Dobrev-less Vampire Diaries (1.4 million) and the Originals (894,000) on Thursday; and Reign (948,000). NBC’s Undateable opened a season of live performances with 2.5 million viewers Friday.
CW's 'The Flash,' which stars Grant Gustin, got off to a fast start with its season premiere Tuesday. (Photo: Cate Cameron, CW)
Comedian in cars talking cars. Jay Leno’s Garage attracted 916,000 viewers for its series premiere Wednesday, making it the most-watched original series broadcast in CNBC history.
Jay Leno tests some wheels as part of his new CNBC series, 'Jay Leno's Garage.' (Photo: Vivian Zink, NBC)
